document.title: Ohio’s Learning Standards – Extended with Learning Progressions Mathematics

74BB35DBCA824675B406EB32302712CA.description: Engage with fractional parts of a shape.

10A749F5778042CF80B05A1F7CF2545D.description: Use models to put together squares or rectangles from equal fractional parts.

97BB98BD7DCC415086471280FCC25739.description: Use models to put together circles from equal fractional parts.

CE28C9DCA4CB4453ABBDAC41C9FA34BF.description: Count the number of sections in a circle that has been divided into equal parts (e.g., half, quarter, third).

C896E347F3114BAC840145805F2DB43F.description: Identify the whole as “two halves,” “four fourths” etc. using real world examples. (i.e. pie, pizza, cookie, etc.)

5D6DC0723BAA410880DC84C98FE73334.description: Partition rectangles into two, four equal parts.

1F7ACC9DDC074CD98670BC3BB8EBEDA5.description: Partition circles into two or four equal parts.

6AE9656D740A4CD1A6A2594447001BAA.description: Describe each equal part as a share of the whole.

208B80F7C1204956838FE9AA4766D8A9.description:
Partition circles and
rectangles into two and
four equal shares, describe
the shares using the words
halves, fourths, and quarters,
and use the phrases half
of, fourth of, and quarter of.
Describe the whole as two of
or four of the shares in realworld contexts. Understand
for these examples that
decomposing into more
equal shares creates smaller
shares.

C8E6FA8F693F43A8838AD977D6D93EEF.description: Identify shapes as two-dimensional or three- dimensional (i.e., flat vs. solid).

244D1854A07244FCABBB4CCDAF8C9CC1.description: Compose 2-D shapes. (i.e. rectangles, squares, trapezoids, triangles, diamond, half-circles, and quarter-circles)

AE935FEE8F3E4597905C78AE4E9EE496.description: Compose 3-D shapes. (i.e.cubes, right rectangular prisms, right circular cones, and right circular cylinders)

8FBB59D9AD3443599B83B891A60C162D.description: Use 2-D shapes (such as attribute blocks or geoboards) to create a new shapes.

EA13B4E2C3DF49A4B87E88E4E9A1C91D.description:
Compose twodimensional shapes
(rectangles, squares,
trapezoids, triangles, halfcircles, and quarter-circles)
or three- dimensional shapes
(cubes, right rectangular
prisms, right circular cones,
and right circular cylinders)
to create a composite shape,
and compose new shapes
from the composite shape.
Students do not need to learn
formal names such as “right
rectangular prism.”

4482836A6A3E4CE8801E20C3DF1C2A78.description: Describe each shape in detail. (i.e. triangles have three sides and three angles)

A9924D5CF8304F6FA99AC9F28757E112.description: Match the term attribute to its definition.

C246F424F2474C199B5B2064A1A49602.description: Identify non-defining attributes. (i.e. color, orientation, overall size)

FA3DAA1C68384B25B41159F812309412.description: Sort shapes by non-defining attributes (size, color, orientation).

30BDACECB9D041EB903354D27BC5EB2E.description: Define attributes of a given shape.

E82468D7ACA54CF58CB950513012A30C.description:
Distinguish between
defining attributes, e.g.,
triangles are closed and
three-sided, versus nondefining attributes, e.g., color,
orientation, overall size;
build and draw shapes that
possess defining attributes.

59C4678CABFB4C8586CBBE6AAA5E02CD.description:
Reason with shapes
and their attributes.

6BAA79110174479A9DDAF3E918034D1A.description: Answer questions about the data in the table. (i.e. how many, more or less...)

727CF7D484DB4A2989921FAAD8976689.description: Ask questions about the data in the table.

8FB4F5B723914D4EBA667652EF97D2A9.description: Identify the total number of data points.

31D6D40D30E547BEB97AEEA3954A087A.description:
Organize, represent,
and interpret data with up
to three categories; ask and
answer questions about the
total number of data points,
how many in each category,
and how many more or less
are in one category than in
another.

3CC614494319473FAF1510BD775FC22D.description:
Work with time and
money.
a. Tell and write time in hours
and half-hours using analog
and digital clocks.
b. Identify pennies and dimes

847B69C823014333BFB9502993379C88.description: Engage with non-traditional measuring tools used to determine length.

CF4BD5E688EC41FCB05575EA1D765AF5.description:
Measure the length of an object with multiple objects of the same size and record the length by object size. (i.e. measure a
pencil using pennies; this pencil is 8 pennies long)

AA2293BF24D6442A9BE81E8FE665A5FA.description:
Express the length of
an object as a whole number
of length units by laying
multiple copies of a shorter
object (the length unit) end
to end; understand that the
length measurement of an
object is the number of samesize length units that span
it with no gaps or overlaps.
Limit to contexts where the
object being measured is
spanned by a whole number
of length units with no gaps or
overlaps.

3DC9A1FDC8CC479A93E842C313EB8AAB.description: Compare the measurements of two objects by discussing lengths.

A6AEE28EE80843C6A777A3258DD353E9.description:
Order three objects by
length; compare the lengths of
two objects indirectly by using
a third object.

8A22D833225F4BC7AC0B17DB0ABC2118.description:
Measure lengths
indirectly and by
iterating length units.

2990B1EABDB14557BDC1E818BA9FFFE1.description: Engage with a group of 10 objects representing the number ten.

D73CA7E090054E4186599E8B64363EA4.description:
Subtract ten objects by placing them on a number line from a given number and counting backward using 1:1
correspondence.

DD1E0FF1678C4F0EB6B5EF8564B18D67.description: Subtract ten objects from a given number by counting back using 1:1 correspondence and a number line as needed.

4E2BDC7ADB9F4C1CA6E6FDD49274A56E.description: Mentally subtract 10 from a given number between 10- 90 and state the number aloud.

Describe the mental process used to subtract ten from a given number to get an answer.(i.e. place value, relationship
between + and -, concrete models, etc.)

Subtract multiples
of 10 in the range 10-90
from multiples of 10 in the
range 10-90 (positive or
zero differences), using
concrete models or drawings
and strategies based on
place value, properties
of operations, and/or the
relationship between addition
and subtraction; relate the
strategy to a written method
and explain the reasoning
used.

70947356D6354AB4B1ACC8BC25431322.description:
Given a two-digit
number, mentally find 10 more
or 10 less than the number,
without having to count;
explain the reasoning used.

Write/organize an addition problem using place value alignment. (i.e.
 48
+10

Describe/outline the order of operations used when adding 2 two-digit numbers. (add the ones to the ones then write the sum
below the ones column and then add the tens to the tens and write that sum below the tens column.

etc. to add 2 two-digit numbers with a sum of 99 or less.

number and a one-digit
number and adding a twodigit number and a multiple
of 10, using concrete models

properties of operations, and/
or the relationship between
addition and subtraction;
record the strategy with a
written numerical method

appropriate, equations)
and explain the reasoning
used. Understand that when
adding two-digit numbers,

sometimes it is necessary to
compose a ten.

62ADBD65C3404B3D93F99D8990F3F1A2.description:

understanding
and properties of
operations to add and
subtract.

6CCE8BAE57264B029D69801C1291CB60.description: Actively engage with two digit numbers or objects representing two digit numbers.

meanings of the tens and
ones digits, recording the

the symbols >, =, and <.

the two digits of a two-digit
number represent amounts of
tens and ones. Understand
the following as special cases:
10 can be thought of as a
bundle of ten ones — called a
“ten;” the numbers from 11 to
19 are composed of a ten and
one, two, three, four, five, six,
seven, eight, or nine ones;
and the numbers 10, 20, 30,
40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90 refer to
one, two, three, four, five, six,
seven, eight, or nine tens (and
0 ones).

Determine the
unknown whole number in
an addition or subtraction
equation relating three whole
numbers. For example,
determine the unknown
number that makes the
equation true in each of the
equations: 8 + = 11; 5 = − 3;
6 + 6 =.

4C7F1DECA4A9429A8FDB4750C62915C0.description: Engage with numbers presented in equations.

98EB11AEA0E145F38AD64EA8F44061D4.description: Engage with visual or tactile representations of the = sign.

487AE8CECC534C2584A431D832F3285A.description: Identify addition sign to mean putting together.

meaning of the equal sign,
and determine if equations
involving addition and
subtraction are true or false.

following equations are true

= 8 – 1; 5 + 2 = 2 + 5; 4 + 1 =
5 + 2.

Work with addition and
subtraction equations.

CBB8947383C84A8E8DD0ADA63CEFDA8A.description: Engage with numbers presented in equations.

B53B55F12ECA40B29B1214736E8284B7.description:
Add and subtract
within 20, demonstrating
fluencyG with various
strategies for addition
and subtraction within 10.
Strategies may include
counting on; making ten, e.g.,
8 + 6 = 8 + 2 + 4 = 10 + 4 =
14; decomposing a number
leading to a ten, e.g., 13 − 4 =
13 − 3 − 1 = 10 − 1 = 9; using
the relationship between
addition and subtraction,
e.g., knowing that 8 + 4 = 12,
one knows 12 − 8 = 4; and
creating equivalent but easier
or known sums, e.g., adding
6 + 7 by creating the known
equivalent 6 + 6 + 1 = 12 + 1
= 13.
